Reading data from the web

Heidi Lumish

String vectors

string_vec = c("my", "name", "is", "heidi")

str_detect(string_vec, "m")
## [1]  TRUE  TRUE FALSE FALSE
str_detect(string_vec, "heidi")
## [1] FALSE FALSE FALSE  TRUE
str_replace(string_vec, "heidi", "Heidi")
## [1] "my"    "name"  "is"    "Heidi"
str_replace(string_vec, "e", "This is an uppercase E")
## [1] "my"                         "namThis is an uppercase E" 
## [3] "is"                         "hThis is an uppercase Eidi"
string_vec = c(
  "i think we all rule for participating",
  "i think i have been caught",
  "i think this will be quite fun actually",
  "it will be fun, i think"
  )

str_detect(string_vec, "i think")
## [1] TRUE TRUE TRUE TRUE
str_detect(string_vec, "^i think")
## [1]  TRUE  TRUE  TRUE FALSE
str_detect(string_vec, "i think$")
## [1] FALSE FALSE FALSE  TRUE
string_vec = c(
  "Y'all remember Pres. HW Bush?",
  "I saw a green bush",
  "BBQ and Bushwalking at Molonglo Gorge",
  "BUSH -- LIVE IN CONCERT!!"
  )

str_detect(string_vec, "bush")
## [1] FALSE  TRUE FALSE FALSE
str_detect(string_vec, "Bush")
## [1]  TRUE FALSE  TRUE FALSE
str_detect(string_vec,"[Bb]ush")
## [1]  TRUE  TRUE  TRUE FALSE

Look for anything that starts with a number followed by letters

string_vec = c(
  '7th inning stretch',
  '1st half soon to begin. Texas won the toss.',
  'she is 5 feet 4 inches tall',
  '3AM - cant sleep :('
  )

str_detect(string_vec, "^[0-9][a-zA-Z]")
## [1]  TRUE  TRUE FALSE  TRUE

Look for 7 followed by anything then 11 (but not 711)

string_vec = c(
  'Its 7:11 in the evening',
  'want to go to 7-11?',
  'my flight is AA711',
  'NetBios: scanning ip 203.167.114.66'
  )

str_detect(string_vec, "7.11")
## [1]  TRUE  TRUE FALSE  TRUE
str_detect(string_vec, "711")
## [1] FALSE FALSE  TRUE FALSE

Look for the open bracket symbol

string_vec = c(
  'The CI is [2, 5]',
  ':-]',
  ':-[',
  'I found the answer on pages [6-7]'
  )

str_detect(string_vec, "\\[")
## [1]  TRUE FALSE  TRUE  TRUE

Why factors are weird

Here we show how you can re-level a factor variable

factor_vec = factor(c("male", "male", "female", "female"))

as.numeric(factor_vec)
## [1] 2 2 1 1
factor_vec = fct_relevel(factor_vec, "male")

as.numeric(factor_vec)
## [1] 1 1 2 2

NSDUH

Remember that slice takes away the first row

nsduh_url = "http://samhda.s3-us-gov-west-1.amazonaws.com/s3fs-public/field-uploads/2k15StateFiles/NSDUHsaeShortTermCHG2015.htm"

table_marj =
  read_html(nsduh_url) %>% 
  html_table() %>% 
  first() %>% 
  slice(-1) %>% view()

Lets clean this up!

The -11 counts backwards from the end to decide where to split

table_marj %>% 
  select(-contains("P Value")) %>% 
  pivot_longer(
    -State,
    names_to = "age_year",
    values_to = "percent") %>% 
  separate(age_year, into = c("age", "year"), -11)
## # A tibble: 560  4

Here we can split based on the open parentheses Then we remove the letters from the percent column Create a data frame

marj_df =
  table_marj %>% 
  select(-contains("P Value")) %>% 
  pivot_longer(
    -State,
    names_to = "age_year",
    values_to = "percent") %>% 
  separate(age_year, into = c("age", "year"), "\\(") %>% 
  mutate(
    year = str_replace(year, "\\)", ""), 
    percent = str_replace(percent, "[a-c]$", ""),
    percent = as.numeric(percent)
  ) %>% 
  filter(!State %in% c("Total U.S.", "Northeast", "Midwest", "South", "West"))

Do dataframe stuff!

marj_df %>% 
  filter(age == "12-17") %>% 
  ggplot(aes(x = State, y = percent, color = year)) +
  geom_point() +
  theme(axis.text.x = element_text(angle = 90, vjust = 0.5, hjust=1))

fct_reorder allows you to order one variable according to another variable

marj_df %>% 
  filter(age == "12-17") %>% 
  mutate(
    State = fct_reorder(State, percent)
  ) %>% 
  ggplot(aes(x = State, y = percent, color = year)) +
  geom_point() +
  theme(axis.text.x = element_text(angle = 90, vjust = 0.5, hjust=1))
